Germany was not allowed to continue military arms production after WWI and wanted to make use of the surplus rifles.  A provision of the treaty would allow them to make sporting arms.  So, several German manufacturers converted the military rifles into shotguns.  This shotgun has the original bolt-face that was produced with the shotgun.  It is an incredibly light shotgun.  This is an interesting piece of history.  If you've got a handgun in your safe that you aren't shooting, let me know.  I'm open to just about anything.  S&W, Ruger, Rock Island, Kel-Tec, Bersa, Taurus, Rossi, Glock, Springfield, etc.  Anything in .22 .38spl, .380, .357, 9mm, .40, .44spl, .45,

title: For Sale:  FAL-style 18" Custom AR-15 carbine. Stag Arms
postcontent:
This is an interesting AR15 variant, built to remedy the ergonomic "zit on the cheerleaders nose" that is the original charging handle. So there's no breaking cheek weld or reaching under a scope, and no slipping fingers grabbing for the little "T." Just a big latch on the left side of the receiver, just like the FAL, and similar to the new SCAR or ACR types.

The other neat thing though is that other than the upper receiver and charging handle assembly, it's a regular AR15, and all parts interchange. The only difference is that the bolt carrier has a small notch milled in it for the charging handle to engage.

Action feels smooth with no hangups. Barrel is *unfired.* It was bought for a rainy day, and has been sitting in a closet unfired and unloved ever since.

Upper receiver: ASA
Lower receiver: Stag Arms
Internals: Rock River (I think), with an aftermarket safety.
Barrel: 18" midlength White Oak from Rainier Arms.

title: For Sale:  Custom made knives
postcontent:
I have several custom hunting knives for sale.  These all have ergonomic antler handles, laminated Scandanavian steel blades and hand made heavy leather sheaths.

The antler makes a great non-slip handle with a curve that fits the hand very naturally.  These are very good for actual work on a downed animal where slipping with a sharp hunting knive can have disasterous results.  The addition of an oversized brass guard adds the additional protection against slipping into a blade, and helps to balance the knife to the junction of the blade and handle.  The guards are hand ground from bar stock, not made of the cheap castings you can find at any supply house.

The blades themselves are a Rockwell 58 inner steel protected with a softer (about a Rockwell 49) outer steel cladding.  The inner steel will literally take a razor edge and will hold it.  I have made these knives for friends and they have reported exceptional blade life, with one person having skinned two elk and a deer before allowing me to touch up the edge.  Anyone who has field experience knows how atypical that is.  The outer cladding is softer to protect the more brittle interior steel from the risk of chipping.  It's the perfect combination in a working knife.  Most of these blades are not stainless as I prefer the quality of the edge they can take.  Some, however, are stainless which still holds a good edge and is more resistant to corrosive environments (such as not wiping the blood off the blade when putting it away).  Non stainless blades are waxed to protect them from moisture.

The sheaths are 9oz cowhide with synthetic sinew stiching.  This gives them a nice rustic versus machine made look.  Each sheath is custom cut for the knife it is to be used with.  

I normally produce a knife with a blade that is between 3 1/2" to 4 1/2" as I have found this length to be the most useful for field work on an animal.  The Bowie I have pictured is about an 7" blade and the flint knife is 5"

I have sold these for $250 each, and they can go for more than that at the shows.  I have several I put together going into this year's Christmas season that are available at about $200.  The flint knife is $100 and the Bowie is only $160.  That is because these are not working knives and so the work needed to make them is less demanding.  The pictures below are representative.  

If interested, let me know.  I can emboss the sheaths with a name or a figure such as a mountain sheep to make it a little more custom for gift giving if you would like.  They're just stamps from Tandy so it's no big deal.

title: Want To Buy:  DONATE UNSAFE OR UNWANTED FIREARMS FOR HUNTER EDUCATION USE
postcontent:
I am a Hunters Safety Education Instructor looking for help. If you have any old, unwanted guns around, unsafe or otherwise, I would like to turn them into non-firing models for use in classes. We can use any firearm, modern or old, any style, about any condition, as long as it's reasonably complete. If you have any old barrels that have been exploded out, that would make a great demonstration tool as well. 

To be clear, this is not something the state or Wildlife and Parks is officially doing at this point. I am looking for tools I can use in my classes, and which I can lend to other instructors for their classes. Currently, we have to use toy guns, which is better than nothing, or our own hunting firearms, which have to be extremely carefully monitored, especially with larger groups. The safer and more effective way is to bring in the real thing, disabled and painted up to show so. This allows us to actually demonstrate safely loading and unloading dummy ammo, as well as ways to verify that a real gun is unloaded, with each student getting a chance for hands-on with a variety of firearm types. Another value of the real thing is in its weight. We can show how carrying a real gun can make arms tired, and the effect of that on safely carrying in the field. 

So, if you have anything you'd like to offer, it would be greatly appreciated.  

Thanks for your time.
Dave
